# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: service-worker-caching
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:service-worker-caching/api-cache] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-cache] It’s been available across browsers since April 2018.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-cache] The **`Cache`** interface provides a persistent storage mechanism for `Request` / `Response` object pairs that are cached in long lived memory.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-cache] How long a `Cache` object lives is browser dependent, but a single origin's scripts can typically rely on the presence of a previously populated `Cache` object.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-cache] Note that the `Cache` interface is exposed to windowed scopes as well as workers.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-cache] You don't have to use it in conjunction with service workers, even though it is defined in the service worker spec.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-cache] An origin can have multiple, named `Cache` objects.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-cache] You are responsible for implementing how your script (e.g., in a `ServiceWorker`) handles `Cache` updates.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-cache] Items in a `Cache` do not get updated unless explicitly requested; they don't expire unless deleted.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-cache] Use `CacheStorage.open()` to open a specific named `Cache` object and then call any of the `Cache` methods to maintain the `Cache`.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-cache] You are also responsible for periodically purging cache entries.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-cache] Each browser has a hard limit on the amount of cache storage that a given origin can use.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-cache] `Cache` quota usage estimates are available via the `StorageManager.estimate()` method.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-cache] The browser does its best to manage disk space, but it may delete the `Cache` storage for an origin.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-cache] The browser will generally delete all of the data for an origin or none of the data for an origin.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-cache] Make sure to version caches by name and use the caches only from the version of the script that they can safely operate on.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-cache] See Deleting old caches for more information.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-cache] Returns a `Promise` that resolves to the response associated with the first matching request in the `Cache` object.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-cache] Returns a `Promise` that resolves to an array of all matching responses in the `Cache` object.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-cache] Takes a URL, retrieves it and adds the resulting response object to the given cache.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-cache] This is functionally equivalent to calling `fetch()`, then using `put()` to add the results to the cache.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-cache] Takes an array of URLs, retrieves them, and adds the resulting response objects to the given cache.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-cache] Takes both a request and its response and adds it to the given cache.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-cache] Finds the `Cache` entry whose key is the request, returning a `Promise` that resolves to `true` if a matching `Cache` entry is found and deleted.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-cache] If no `Cache` entry is found, the promise resolves to `false`.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-cache] Returns a `Promise` that resolves to an array of `Cache` keys.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-cache] This code snippet is from the service worker selective caching sample.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-cache] (see selective caching live) The code uses `CacheStorage.open()` to open any `Cache` objects with a `Content-Type` header that starts with `font/`.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-cache] The code then uses `Cache.match()` to see if there's already a matching font in the cache, and if so, returns it.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-cache] If there isn't a matching font, the code fetches the font from the network and uses `Cache.put()` to cache the fetched resource.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-cache] The code handles exceptions thrown from the `fetch()` operation.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-cache] Note that an HTTP error response (e.g., 404) will not trigger an exception.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-cache] It will return a normal response object that has the appropriate error code.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-cache] The code snippet also shows a best practice for versioning caches used by the service worker.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-cache] Though there's only one cache in this example, the same approach can be used for multiple caches.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-cache] It maps a shorthand identifier for a cache to a specific, versioned cache name.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-cache] The code also deletes all caches that aren't named in `CURRENT_CACHES`.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-cache] In the code example, `caches` is a property of the `ServiceWorkerGlobalScope`.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-cache] It holds the `CacheStorage` object, by which it can access the `CacheStorage` interface.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-cache] The Fetch API requires `Set-Cookie` headers to be stripped before returning a `Response` object from `fetch()`.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-cache] So a `Response` stored in a `Cache` won't contain `Set-Cookie` headers, and therefore won't cause any cookies to be stored.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-fetch-api] The Fetch API provides an interface for fetching resources (including across the network).
[src:service-worker-caching/api-fetch-api] It is a more powerful and flexible replacement for `XMLHttpRequest`.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-fetch-api] The Fetch API uses `Request` and `Response` objects (and other things involved with network requests), as well as related concepts such as CORS and the HTTP Origin header semantics.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-fetch-api] For making a request and fetching a resource, use the `fetch()` method.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-fetch-api] It is a global method in both `Window` and `Worker` contexts.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-fetch-api] This makes it available in pretty much any context you might want to fetch resources in.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-fetch-api] The `fetch()` method takes one mandatory argument, the path to the resource you want to fetch.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-fetch-api] It returns a `Promise` that resolves to the `Response` to that request — as soon as the server responds with headers — **even if the server response is an HTTP error status**.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-fetch-api] You can also optionally pass in an `init` options object as the second argument (see `Request`).
[src:service-worker-caching/api-fetch-api] Once a `Response` is retrieved, there are a number of methods available to define what the body content is and how it should be handled.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-fetch-api] You can create a request and response directly using the `Request()` and `Response()` constructors, but it's uncommon to do this directly.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-fetch-api] Instead, these are more likely to be created as results of other API actions (for example, `FetchEvent.respondWith()` from service workers).
[src:service-worker-caching/api-fetch-api] Find out more about using the Fetch API features in Using Fetch.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-fetch-api] The `fetchLater()` API enables a developer to request a *deferred fetch*, that can be sent after a specified period of time, or when the page is closed or navigated away from.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-fetch-api] The `fetch()` method used to fetch a resource.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-fetch-api] Represents the set of options that can be used to configure a deferred fetch request.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-fetch-api] Represents the result of requesting a deferred fetch.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-fetch-api] Represents response/request headers, allowing you to query them and take different actions depending on the results.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-fetch-api] Controls the top-level quota for the `fetchLater()` API.
[src:service-worker-caching/api-fetch-api] Controls the shared cross-origin subframe quota for the `fetchLater()` API.
[src:service-worker-caching/cachestorage] The **`CacheStorage`** interface represents the storage for `Cache` objects.
[src:service-worker-caching/cachestorage] Use `CacheStorage.open()` to obtain a `Cache` instance.
[src:service-worker-caching/cachestorage] Use `CacheStorage.match()` to check if a given `Request` is a key in any of the `Cache` objects that the `CacheStorage` object tracks.
[src:service-worker-caching/cachestorage] You can access `CacheStorage` through the `Window.caches` property in windows or through the `WorkerGlobalScope.caches` property in workers.
[src:service-worker-caching/cachestorage] Checks if a given `Request` is a key in any of the `Cache` objects that the `CacheStorage` object tracks, and returns a `Promise` that resolves to that match.
[src:service-worker-caching/cachestorage] Returns a `Promise` that resolves to `true` if a `Cache` object matching the `cacheName` exists.
[src:service-worker-caching/cachestorage] Finds the `Cache` object matching the `cacheName`, and if found, deletes the `Cache` object and returns a `Promise` that resolves to `true`.
[src:service-worker-caching/cachestorage] If no `Cache` object is found, it resolves to `false`.
[src:service-worker-caching/cachestorage] Returns a `Promise` that will resolve with an array containing strings corresponding to all of the named `Cache` objects tracked by the `CacheStorage`.
[src:service-worker-caching/cachestorage] Use this method to iterate over a list of all the `Cache` objects.
[src:service-worker-caching/cachestorage] This code snippet is from the MDN simple service worker example (see simple service worker running live.) This service worker script waits for an `install` event to fire, then runs `waitUntil` to handle the install process for the app.
[src:service-worker-caching/cachestorage] This consists of calling `CacheStorage.open` to create a new cache, then using `Cache.addAll` to add a series of assets to it.
[src:service-worker-caching/cachestorage] In the second code block, we wait for a `FetchEvent` to fire.
[src:service-worker-caching/cachestorage] If this fails (e.g., because the network is down), return a fallback response.
[src:service-worker-caching/cachestorage] Finally, return whatever the custom response ended up being equal to, using `FetchEvent.respondWith`.
[src:service-worker-caching/cachestorage] This snippet shows how the API can be used outside of a service worker context, and uses the `await` operator for much more readable code.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] When a user opens and interacts with a website, all the resources that the website needs, including the HTML, JavaScript, CSS, images, fonts, as well as any data explicitly requested by the app, are retrieved by making HTTP(S) requests.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] One of the most fundamental features of a PWA is the ability to explicitly cache some of the app's resources on the device, meaning that they can be retrieved without needing to send a request to the network.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] There are two main benefits to caching resources locally: **offline operation** and **responsiveness**.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] The main drawback, of course, is **freshness**: caching is less appropriate for resources which need to be up to date.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] Also, for some types of requests, such as POST requests, caching is never appropriate.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] This means that whether and when you should cache a resource is very dependent on the resource in question, and a PWA will typically adopt different strategies for different resources.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] In this guide we'll look at some common caching strategies for PWAs, and see which strategies make sense for which resources.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] The main technologies on which a PWA can build a caching strategy are the Fetch API, the Service Worker API, and the Cache API.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] The Fetch API defines a global function `fetch()` for fetching a network resource, and `Request` and `Response` interfaces that represent network requests and responses.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] The `fetch()` function takes a `Request` or a URL as an argument, and returns a `Promise` that resolves to a `Response`.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] The `fetch()` function is available to service workers as well as to the main app thread.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] A service worker is a part of a PWA: it's a separate script that runs in its own thread, separate from the app's main thread.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] Once the service worker is active, then whenever the app requests a network resource controlled by the service worker, the browser fires an event called `fetch` in the service worker's global scope.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] This event is fired not only for explicit `fetch()` calls from the main thread, but also implicit network requests to load pages and subresources (such as JavaScript, CSS, and images) made by the browser following page navigation.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] By listening for the `fetch` event, the service worker can intercept the request and return a customized `Response`.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] In particular, it can return a locally cached response instead of always going to the network, or return a locally cached response if the device is offline.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] The `Cache` interface provides persistent storage for `Request`/`Response` pairs.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] It provides methods to add and delete `Request`/`Response` pairs, and to look up a cached `Response` matching a given `Request`.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] The cache is available in both the main app thread and the service worker: so it is possible for one thread to add a response there, and the other to retrieve it.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] Most commonly, the service worker will add resources to the cache in its `install` or `fetch` event handlers.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] A caching strategy is an algorithm for when to cache a resource, when to serve a cached resource, and when to get the resource from the network.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] In this section we'll summarize some common strategies.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] This isn't an exhaustive list: it's just intended to illustrate the kinds of approaches a PWA can take.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] A caching strategy balances offline operation, responsiveness, and freshness.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] Different resources have different requirements here: for example, the app's basic UI is likely to be relatively static, while it may be essential to have fresh data when displaying a product listing.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] This means that a PWA will typically adopt different strategies for different resources, and a single PWA might use all the strategies described here.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] In this strategy we will precache some resources, and then implement a "cache first" strategy only for those resources.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] Precaching is an appropriate strategy for resources that the PWA is certain to need, that will not change for this version of the app, and that need to be fetched as quickly as possible.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] That includes, for example, the basic user interface of the app.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] If this is precached, then the app's UI can be rendered on launch without needing any network requests.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] In the `install` event handler, we pass the result of the caching operation into the event's `waitUntil()` method.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] This means that if caching fails for any reason, the installation of the service worker fails: conversely, if installation succeeded, the service worker can be sure that the resource was added to the cache.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] We return the resource by calling the event's `respondWith()` method.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] If we don't call `respondWith()` for a given request, then the request is sent to the network as if the service worker had not intercepted it.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] So if a request is not precached, it just goes to the network.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] When we add `networkResponse` to the cache, we must clone the response and add the copy to the cache, returning the original.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] This is because `Response` objects are streamable, so may only be read once.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] You might wonder why we fall back to the network for precached resources.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] If they are precached, can't we be sure they will be in the cache?
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] The reason is that it is possible for the cache to be cleared, either by the browser or by the user.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] Although this is unlikely, it would make the PWA unusable unless it can fall back to the network.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] The drawback of "cache first" is that once a response is in the cache, it is never refreshed until a new version of the service worker is installed.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] The "cache first with cache refresh" strategy, also known as "stale while revalidate", is similar to "cache first", except that we always send the request to the network, even after a cache hit, and use the response to refresh the cache.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] This means we get the responsiveness of "cache first", but get a fairly fresh response (as long as the request is made reasonably often).
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] This is a good choice when responsiveness is important, and freshness is somewhat important but not essential.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] In this version we implement "cache first with cache refresh" for all resources except JSON.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] Note that we update the cache asynchronously (in a `then()` handler), so the app does not have to wait for the network response to be received before it can use the cached response.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] The last strategy we'll look at, "network first", is the inverse of cache first: we try to retrieve the resource from the network.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] If the network request succeeds, we return the response and update the cache.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] This is useful for requests for which it is important to get the most fresh response possible, but for which a cached resource is better than nothing.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] A messaging app's list of recent messages might fall into this category.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] In the example below we use "network first" for requests to fetch all resources located under the app's "inbox" path.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] There are still requests for which no response is better than a possibly-outdated response, and for which only a "network only" strategy is appropriate.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] For example, if an app is showing the list of available products, it will be frustrating to users if the list is out of date.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] Caches have a limited amount of storage space, and the browser may evict an app's cached data if the limit is exceeded.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] The specific limits and behavior are browser-specific: see Storage quotas and eviction criteria for details.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] In practice, eviction of cached data is a very rare event.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] The user can also clear an app's cache at any time.
[src:service-worker-caching/guides-caching] A PWA should clean up any old versions of its cache in the service worker's `activate` event: when this event fires, the service worker can be sure that no previous versions of the service worker are running, so old cached data is no longer needed.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] Service workers essentially act as proxy servers that sit between web applications, the browser, and the network (when available).
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] They are intended, among other things, to enable the creation of effective offline experiences, intercept network requests, and take appropriate action based on whether the network is available, and update assets residing on the server.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] They will also allow access to push notifications and background sync APIs.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] A service worker is an event-driven worker registered against an origin and a path.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] Service workers run in a worker context: they therefore have no DOM access and run on a different thread to the main JavaScript that powers your app.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] They are non-blocking and designed to be fully asynchronous.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] As a consequence, APIs such as synchronous XHR and Web Storage can't be used inside a service worker.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] Service workers can't import JavaScript modules dynamically, and `import()` will throw an error if it is called in a service worker global scope.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] Static imports using the `import` statement are allowed.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] Service workers are only available in secure contexts: this means that their document is served over HTTPS, although browsers also treat `http://localhost` as a secure context, to facilitate local development.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] HTTP connections are susceptible to malicious code injection by man in the middle attacks, and such attacks could be worse if allowed access to these powerful APIs.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] A service worker is first registered using the `ServiceWorkerContainer.register()` method.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] If successful, your service worker will be downloaded to the client and attempt installation/activation (see below) for URLs accessed by the user inside the whole origin, or a subset specified by you.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] The service worker is immediately downloaded when a user first accesses a service worker–controlled site/page.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] Installation is attempted when the downloaded file is found to be new — either different to an existing service worker (byte-wise compared), or the first service worker encountered for this page/site.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] If this is the first time a service worker has been made available, installation is attempted, then after a successful installation, it is activated.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] If there is an existing service worker available, the new version is installed in the background, but not yet activated — at this point it is called the *worker in waiting*.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] It is only activated when there are no longer any pages loaded that are still using the old service worker.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] As soon as there are no more pages to be loaded, the new service worker activates (becoming the *active worker*).
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] Activation can happen sooner using `ServiceWorkerGlobalScope.skipWaiting()` and existing pages can be claimed by the active worker using `Clients.claim()`.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] You can listen for the `install` event; a standard action is to prepare your service worker for usage when this fires, for example by creating a cache using the built-in storage API, and placing assets inside it that you'll want for running your app offline.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] The point where this event fires is generally a good time to clean up old caches and other things associated with the previous version of your service worker.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] Your service worker can respond to requests using the `FetchEvent` event.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] You can modify the response to these requests in any way you want, using the `FetchEvent.respondWith()` method.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] For a complete tutorial to show how to build up your first basic example, read Using Service Workers.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] Service workers can incur an unnecessary performance cost — when a page is loaded for the first time in a while, the browser has to wait for the service worker to start up and run to know what content to load and whether it should come from a cache or the network.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] If you already know ahead of time where certain content should be fetched from, you can bypass the service worker altogether and fetch resources immediately.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] The `InstallEvent.addRoutes()` method can be used to implement this use case and more.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] In the future, service workers will be able to do several other useful things for the web platform that will bring it closer to native app viability.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] Represents the storage for `Request` / `Response` object pairs that are cached as part of the `ServiceWorker` life cycle.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] Represents the storage for `Cache` objects.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] It provides a master directory of all the named caches that a `ServiceWorker` can access, and maintains a mapping of string names to corresponding `Cache` objects.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] Represents the scope of a service worker client.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] A service worker client is either a document in a browser context or a `SharedWorker`, which is controlled by an active worker.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] Represents a container for a list of `Client` objects; the main way to access the active service worker clients at the current origin.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] Extends the lifetime of the `install` and `activate` events dispatched on the `ServiceWorkerGlobalScope`, as part of the service worker lifecycle.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] This ensures that any functional events (like `FetchEvent`) are not dispatched to the `ServiceWorker`, until it upgrades database schemas, and deletes outdated cache entries, etc.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] The event object of a `message` event fired on a service worker (when a channel message is received on the `ServiceWorkerGlobalScope` from another context) — extends the lifetime of such events.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] The parameter passed into the `onfetch` handler, `FetchEvent` represents a fetch action that is dispatched on the `ServiceWorkerGlobalScope` of a `ServiceWorker`.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] It contains information about the request and resulting response, and provides the `FetchEvent.respondWith()` method, which allows us to provide an arbitrary response back to the controlled page.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] The parameter passed into an `install` event handler function, the `InstallEvent` interface represents an install action that is dispatched on the `ServiceWorkerGlobalScope` of a `ServiceWorker`.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] As a child of `ExtendableEvent`, it ensures that functional events such as `FetchEvent` are not dispatched during installation.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] Provides methods for managing the preloading of resources with a service worker.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] Multiple browsing contexts (e.g., pages, workers, etc.) can be associated with the same `ServiceWorker` object.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] Provides an object representing the service worker as an overall unit in the network ecosystem, including facilities to register, unregister, and update service workers, and access the state of service workers and their registrations.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] Represents the global execution context of a service worker.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] Represents a service worker registration.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] Represents the scope of a service worker client that is a document in a browser context, controlled by an active worker.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] This is a special type of `Client` object, with some additional methods and properties available.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] Returns the `CacheStorage` object associated with the current context.
[src:service-worker-caching/service-worker-api] Returns a `ServiceWorkerContainer` object, which provides access to registration, removal, upgrade, and communication with the `ServiceWorker` objects for the associated document.
